source: Here is a (slightly longer than) toot-length crash course in what I mean by dad-ification:
translation: I think there are two main components to dad-ification: homogeneity and technical skill. Dad culture tends to be very homogeneous, meaning that people within it generally think and behave similarly. They may be into the same movies, games, or sports, and they may share a sense of humor or a particular style of dress. This homogeneity is probably one of the reasons why dad culture is so appealing to so many people. When you're around other dads, you feel like you fit in, and that sense of belonging is really important. As for technical skill, dads tend to excel at certain types of activities that require patience, precision, and attention to detail. They might be handy around the house, able to fix all sorts of things, or they may be great at building things like furniture or other structures. They might also be skilled at working with their hands, whether it's fixing cars, working in the yard, or doing other DIY projects. Overall, dad-ification seems to be about finding ways to connect with other people in a meaningful way that involves a certain set of skills and interests.
reference: 以下是关于我所说的“父亲化”的简单概述（略长）：
